      <div xml:id="NA39-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iraṇṭāṅ kūṭṭattu etircciyiṉ (EV: etircciyilē) talaivaṉ colliyatu.
            (ET: = 2., 1. itu talaivi nāṇik kaṇputaittuḻit talaivaṉ colliyatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said when he was opposed at the second meeting. (EV: This is what HE said when SHE covered her eyes [with her hands] in shame.)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA39">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            colliṟ colletir koḷḷā yāḻaniṉ</l>
<l>            ṟirumuka miṟaiñci nāṇuti katumeṉak</l>
<l>            kāmaṅ kaimmikiṟ ṟāṅkuta leḷitō</l>
<l>            koṭuṅkē ḻirumpuṟa naṭuṅkak kuttip</l>
<l>            puliviḷai yāṭiya pulavunāṟu vēḻattiṉ </l>
<l>            ṟalaimarup pēyppak kaṭaimaṇi civantaniṉ</l>
<l>            kaṇṇē katava valla naṇṇā</l>
<l>            raraṇṭalai matila rākavu muracukoṇ</l>
<l>            ṭōmparaṇ kaṭanta vaṭupōrc ceḻiyaṉ</l>
<l>            perumpeyark kūṭa laṉṉaniṉ </l>
<l>            karumpuṭait tōḷu muṭaiyavā laṇaṅkē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

<l>If [I] speak you don't receive [my] words. Bowing</l>
<l>your brilliant face you would be ashamed. Is it easy</l>
<l>to endure when desire exceeds the limit, harshly(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">katum</term> is one of the difficult ideophones. Is it a writing variant of <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭum</term> (cf. KT 294.3)?</note>?</l>
<l>Rimmed jewels<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṭai maṇi</term> is a formula (cf. Cilap. 20.54) refering to the eyes, whether in a metaphoric way or as a lexeme denoting the eye-ball is not clear.</note> that have become red</l>
<l rend="indent4">like the tusks of the elephant,</l>
<l rend="indent">that smells of flesh since he played with the tiger [and] gored,</l>
<l rend="indent">[for him] to shiver, [his] dark back with curved lustrous [stripes],<note place="foot">T.V.G. takes <term xml:lang="ta">kēḻ</term> to refer to the stripes of the tiger, but this is not backed up by the lexica. We could, however, see a metaphor: the curved lustre of the tiger is its stripes.</note></l>
<l>your eyes, they are not angry.</l>
<l rend="indent">Like the famous Kūṭal of Ceḻiyaṉ, in deathly battle,</l>
<l rend="indent">who took [his] drum [and] surmounted the protected</l>
<l rend="indent">fortress, even when there were defenders in the foes’ fortress,</l>
<l>your shoulders too, [drawn]<note place="foot">For shoulders drawn with sugarcane cf. KT 384.1, NA 289.7.</note> with sugar-cane,</l>
<l>are indeed full of torment [for me].</l>
        </lg>
